'''{{lang|pt|Português macarrônico}}''' ({{IPA-pt|puʁtuˈgez mɐkɐˈʁõniku}}, "macaronic Portuguese", pronounced {{IPA-all|portʊˈgeːz(e) makaˈrɔːniko|}} by its speakers) is an [[Italian language|Italian]]-[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] [[macaronic language]] that was widely spoken by [[Italian Brazilian|Italian immigrants]] in [[Brazil]] (especially in the [[Greater São Paulo]] area and elsewhere in the [[São Paulo (state)|São Paulo state]]) well into the 1950s.

It is not to be confused with the more strongly conserved [[Talian dialect]], based primarily with [[Venetian language|Venetian]] lexicon and grammar, and contribution of other northern Italian languages, and spoken by more isolated communities primarily in southern Brazil and Espírito Santo, while {{lang|pt|macarrônico}} is a more characteristically urban code-switching that often fades away with time according to the speaker.

In spite of its near-extinction, it significantly influenced the Portuguese spoken by people in the state of São Paulo, most importantly when it comes to the {{lang|pt|paulistano}} dialect.

